    "methodology": "Fuel poverty in England is measured using the Low Income Low Energy Efficiency (LILEE) metric. A household is fuel poor if it has a low income (below the poverty line after energy costs) AND low energy efficiency (below band C on its EPC). This replaced the earlier 10% of income definition in 2014. Energy price cap data represents the annual bill estimate for a typical household (2,900 kWh electricity, 12,000 kWh gas).",
    "knownIssues": [
      "Change in definition in 2014 makes pre/post comparison difficult",
      "LILEE metric does not capture households that ARE energy efficient but cannot afford bills due to very low income",
